Holagraph Peaceful‑Use License (HPUL‑1.0)
Copyright © 2026 David E. Blackwell

Preamble
The Holagraph Slab Framework, including all equations, control laws, emitter‑grid
architectures, simulations, hardware requirements, and derivative concepts, is released
freely for peaceful, civilian, scientific, artistic, exploratory, and humanitarian use.
This license exists to prevent militarization, coercive applications, and harmful use of
the framework in any form.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Allowed Uses
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Holagraph Framework may be used for:
• scientific research
• artistic and media development
• immersive environments
• civilian exploration and spacecraft interfaces
• educational and humanitarian technologies
• peaceful technological advancement

All allowed uses must comply with Sections 3–9 of this license.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Prohibited Uses
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Holagraph Framework may NOT be used for:
• weapons or weapons-adjacent systems
• military targeting, tracking, or combat platforms
• intelligence, surveillance, or coercive technologies
• government use in conflict zones
• harmful, oppressive, or violent applications

Legal Basis:
• Geneva Conventions (1949)
• Hague Convention IV (1907)
• UN Charter Articles 1, 2(4), and 55
• Rome Statute Articles 7 and 8

Any violation constitutes misuse of civilian scientific work for hostile purposes.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Humanitarian Exceptions
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The following uses are permitted:
• hospitals and medical facilities
• ambulances and emergency medical services
• civilian rescue operations
• accredited journalists in conflict zones
• UN peacekeeping observers

Legal Basis:
• Geneva Convention I (Medical Neutrality)
• UN Security Council Resolution 1738
• Customary IHL Rule 25

----------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Derivative Works
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Any technology that uses:
• the equations in Section 6 of the manuscript
• emitter‑grid interference
• phase‑locked optical surfaces
• reinforcement feedback
• or any mathematical/engineering extension

is considered a derivative work.

All derivative works MUST:
• acknowledge the original author
• remain open-source
• follow peaceful‑use restrictions
• provide a prototype to the author and family
• release firmware and schematics openly
• remain available for scientific review

Legal Basis:
• Berne Convention Article 2(3)
• Title 17 U.S.C. §101 and §106A

----------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Commercial Use Requirements
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Any commercial device derived from this framework MUST:
• be repairable and modular
• include full schematics and wiring diagrams
• include a bill of materials (BOM)
• use open-source firmware and operating systems
• avoid DRM, encryption lockouts, and cloud activation
• avoid subscription‑locked functionality
• provide one full working prototype to the author and his immediate family

Legal Basis:
• Magnuson‑Moss Warranty Act (15 U.S.C. §2301–2312)
• DMCA §1201 repair exemptions
• EU Ecodesign Directive 2009/125/EC
• EU Right‑to‑Repair Regulation (2021/341)
• EU Digital Markets Act (2022/1925)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Open Firmware Requirement
----------------------------------------------------------------------
All firmware, drivers, and operating systems MUST be:
• free
• open-source
• modifiable by the user
• not encrypted to block repair
• not tied to proprietary cloud services
• not behind paywalls

Firmware must be licensed under:
• GPLv3, AGPLv3, Apache 2.0, MIT, or equivalent

----------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Anti‑Lockdown Clause
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Manufacturers may NOT:
• use DRM to block repair
• encrypt firmware to prevent modification
• disable devices remotely
• tie hardware to proprietary ecosystems
• require cloud activation for basic functionality

Legal Basis:
• DMCA §1201 exemptions
• FTC v. Harley‑Davidson (2022)
• EU DMA Article 5(5)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Crimes Against Humanity Clause
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Any use of this framework that results in:
• harm
• coercion
• targeting
• military deployment
• or civilian injury

is considered a crime against humanity under:
• Rome Statute Article 7
• Rome Statute Article 8
• Geneva Conventions (grave breaches)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Termination
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Any violation of:
• peaceful‑use restrictions
• open‑hardware requirements
• prototype obligations
• or anti‑military clauses

immediately terminates this license.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
10. Jurisdiction
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This license is enforceable under:
• Berne Convention
• U.S. Copyright Act Title 17
• International Humanitarian Law
• EU Digital Markets and Right‑to‑Repair regulations

----------------------------------------------------------------------
End of License
----------------------------------------------------------------------
